Intro


Doubles is a 2-4 player Pong-like with a competitive focus. It aims to be as accessible as arcade games like foosball or air hockey, while capturing some of the nuances of those games. It’s developed by me, with music & sound by jaxcheese.


Controls


Doubles can be controlled with a keyboard or gamepad*. For multiplayer at least one gamepad is required.


*Tested with DUALSHOCK®4 Wireless Controller & Xbox Wireless Controller

Left analog stick, left / right

  • Move inner paddle (or menu cursor) anticlockwise / clockwise

Control modes


Paddles are by default controlled independently of each other. While this allows for more nuanced play, it can feel a bit like patting your head & rubbing your tummy at first. A less unintuitive ‘tethered’ mode exists as an alternative control scheme, which moves both inner & outer paddles in tandem (&, because they sit in different orbits, they’ll quickly go out of sync with each other, allowing for more advanced play despite the handicap). This mode can be toggled on the fly; a ’t’ will appear beside the player’s score to indicate when it’s enabled.


Note #1 — 4 players


The current build can only be played with up to two players; the final build will support up to four. With four players the issue described above will no longer be relevant.


Note #2 — arcade/Switch controls


Rotating an object in a circle with effectively two buttons (left & right) is not particularly intuitive. The main problem arises when the object is in the lower half of its orbit—pressing left here will move the object ‘right’ (anticlockwise), & right ‘left’ (clockwise). I’ve personally found that this confusion diminishes over time, but ideally it wouldn’t be an issue to begin with.


I’ve tried multiple different control schemes to alleviate this issue, without success. The most promising one in my head was to map analog stick movement directly to paddle position. With these controls pushing the analog stick in the 3 o’clock direction would rotate the paddle to the 3 o’clock position in the game. But in practice I found this was far more confusing, since I couldn’t anticipate which way the paddle would move at any given moment (e.g. if the paddle was just past the 3 o’clock position it would move in an anticlockwise rotation, if just before then clockwise).


I’ve had more success in this regard with altering the game’s graphics. The circles that indicate the paddle orbits used to be static, but now rotate as the paddles move (there are four rings now instead of two, one per paddle). This is to emphasise that ‘left’ means ‘move anticlockwise’, not ‘move left’, & ‘right’ ‘move clockwise’, not ‘move right’. It isn’t a perfect solution, but it’s the best I could come up with considering the limitations of a gamepad/keyboard.



Which got me thinking—what if I wasn’t limited to conventional button controls? What if instead of an analog stick I had access to a rotary controller like a knob or spinner? Wouldn’t this solve the problem more or less singlehandedly? I think it might. An arcade-like spinner with some inertia could improve the game tenfold I feel, & in an arcade-like setup with four spinners (& four buttons), it would be closer to matching the foosball experience. Like with foosball there would be no need to distinguish between a two player & four player mode—the additional players would simply take the place of player 1 & player 2’s second hand.



I might be able to replicate something similar to this with Switch Joy-Con controllers. Tilting the Joy-Con one way could rotate the paddle clockwise, & anticlockwise in the other direction. This obviously wouldn’t be as tactile a solution as the arcade one, but could be a happy compromise for putting the game on commercial hardware.


(Note: though I intend to trial out the arcade setup imminently, it will be expensive to accrue all the parts. I’ll start with one spinner & go from there.)


Move set/mechanics


Here are some of the moves available to the player. Many of them are simply emergent, resulting from the game’s basic premise (‘Pong, but in a circle, with an extra paddle per side’). Others are more contrived, but are hopefully consistent & therefore congruent with the rest of the game’s design.


Legend


Attack cost (AC)


The amount of damage a paddle will take when executing the specified move. When one paddle takes damage, the other gains that much health, so the combined health/length of the two paddles is always equal (i.e. 4, unless the ball is being passed).


Defence cost (DC)


The amount of damage a paddle will take when returning the specified move


Basic


Forehand (AC: 1, DC: 1)


The most basic move in the game; reflects the ball on impact



(Note: doesn’t rely on Unity physics, since the ball can otherwise end up behind the paddle if it collides with the paddle edge—this is impossible to return when it’s the outer paddle. Reflections are always in the opposite direction to the collision for this reason.)


Vector2 newDir = Vector2.Reflect(RecordedVelocity, collisionNormal).normalized;
rigidbody.velocity = newDir * ballSpeed;


Slice (AC: 1, DC: 1)


Occurs when the reflected angle is greater than 45°; can be particularly challenging to return



Backhand (AC: 1, DC: 1)


Occurs when the ball collides with the back of the paddle. It is particularly effective for scoring, since it reflects the ball directly away from the playfield & gives less room for the opposing player to react.



Advanced


Smash (AC: 2, DC: 4)


When a paddle is down to zero health it will leave a trail as it moves. If the ball passes through this trail it will become charged.




A charged ball will be smashed when it next collides, doubling its speed until the next collision



(Note: the inner paddle will usually be the one charging the ball, & the outer paddle smashing. In some arenas you can do the opposite, if the ball happens to bounce off an obstacle once it is charged.)


Split (AC: NA, DC: 4)


A smashed ball can again be charged by the opposing player, which puts the ball in a smash-charged state. If the ball manages to connect with another paddle while in this state it will split into two. Both balls will be smashed.



Refract (AC: NA, DC: NA)


When a ball passes through a paddle of the opposing colour, from behind, its velocity will bend towards the direction it’s facing. You can use this mechanic to divert the ball immediately after returning it with the outer paddle, confusing your opponent.



Expert


Refract smash (AC: NA, DC: NA)


You can refract a smashed ball if it manages to ricochet off an obstacle in certain arenas



Pass (AC: 0, DC: NA)


If the ball collides with a paddle whilst the pass button is held down it won’t change colour. Instead the collided paddle will temporarily lose one health point, without affecting the other paddle. Once the ball collides with a paddle with the pass button released it will resume its size prior to passing minus one (i.e. the regular cost of a collision, unless the ball was smashed); the other will follow suit accordingly.



Because the paddles will become progressively smaller with each pass, the number of passes you can perform in one turn is limited to their size prior to passing. The most is 3 (when the paddles have 2 health points each).


(Note: I considered adding a timing element to passing, so that a perfectly timed pass would prevent the paddle from taking damage. This would increase the potential number of passes that a skilled player could make per turn, which could have interesting consequences, e.g. they could pass the ball right round the playfield in a wide circle. However, passing inherently slows down the frenetic nature of the game, plus it would introduce an execution challenge which I feel is incongruous with the rest of the design. Therefore it was scrapped.)


Variable scoring


In a later build I plan to expose this move set in a settings screen, to allow players to configure how many points each move nets upon scoring. Smashes could score you two points instead of one for example, or backhands no points if you want to discourage them for whatever reason.


Arenas


There are currently three arenas to choose from. These are boringly named by number, but will have more descriptive names in the final build. There’s plenty of scope for adding more arenas, perhaps even altering the win condition in some of them, which I intend to do in later builds.


Arena #1


The default arena, which was the only one available for most of development. This game’s [Final Destination](https://www.ssbwiki.com/Final_Destination_(SSBM)) or Training Stage.


Arena #2


A ring of blocks lines the arena perimeter. Aim for the gaps to score, or smash the ball at a block to knock it out of orbit. The ring can be set to rotate at variable speeds.



Arena #3


A configurable number of balls occupies the playfield. These will deflect the ball, but will also be pushed on impact.



UI


To help familiarise players with the controls, all of the menus are presented as circles. Options are selected by spinning & pointing a cursor at the desired option, then hitting the confirm button. All players can control the menu cursor at the same time so that everyone can practice (might add a cursor per player in the final build).



(Note: need to implement a snap-to-option solution)


Aesthetic


The game’s graphics should above all prioritise readability, but should also be bright & colourful to emphasise the fun :) I’ve used a simple vector style to achieve this (mostly because that’s what I’m able to make by myself), with a healthy dose of rounded corners & rounded text.


Colour palette


The palette has more or less remained the same since the original prototype. I had taken it from a website, but I can’t recall which. Alternative colour palettes might be a thing in the final build.
